\i\b \cf0 ###### Behaviorism as a treatment in psychiatry
\f0\i0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120

\f1 \cf0 \
Behavioral treatments in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scrivcmt://C053555C-5E16-476D-8730-EF01530390E0"}}{\fldrslt psychiatry}}, like behaviorism in psychology, follows from a deceptively simple insight: that psychiatric treatment aims at the cessation of maladaptive behavior.  Like psychoanalysis, behavioral therapies restrict themselves to neurosis, not psychosis.
\f0 \

\f1 \
There are two major kinds of inhibition therapies found in the literature:
\f0 \

\f1 \
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-360\sa120

\f0 \cf0 * 
\f1 Reciprocal inhibition, developed by Wolpe, involves diminishing the maladaptive behavior by conditioning a new behavior in response to a given stimulus that is incompatible with the undesired behavior. For reciprocal inhibition to work, the maladaptive behavior
\i  must be
\i0  incompatible with the new conditioned behavior. Aversion therapy, which exposes the subject to the object of desire and conditions a new negative response, is a form of reciprocal inhibition.
\f0 \
* 
\f1 Transmarginal inhibition, also known as
\i  flooding
\i0 , involves exposing the patient to strong examples of the stimuli for prolonged periods.
\f0 \
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-360\sa120

\f1 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa120
\cf0 Other inhibition therapies, such as 'retroactive inhibition' are usually forms of reciprocal inhibition.
\f0 \

